[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage III, T2, N1, resected, upper rectal cancer
I discussed with the patient, also with Dr. Sumrall, that currently because he has stage III disease, we do recommend adjuvant chemoradiation therapy.  Standard therapy would include probably about two-months of FOLFOX with 5-FU bolus for four treatments, then followed by concurrent chemoradiation with 5-FU and radiation for about a month, then afterward with FOLFOX for about another two-months.  Post-radiation, there may be more toxicity, and then the 5-FU bolus could be omitted, if needed.  I explained this.  I explained side-effects associated with chemo, in general, including nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, GI side-effects as well as hand/foot rashes and numbness and tingling in the fingers/hands and cold sensitivity.  Patient expressed a wish to be treated at-home because he is living five hours away.  I asked him to get connected with a local oncologist soon because he is about a month after the surgery right now.  I told him the adjuvant chemoradiation usually started within about four to eight weeks after the surgery.  The patient also wanted to get radiation administered at-home.  I talked to him that I would recommend to him to talk to our radiation oncologists to get an opinion about side-effects and benefits.  He is willing to consider.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at BH.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

